1
00:00:15,749 --> 00:00:18,479
Good evening,
and welcome to <i>The Culpeper Minute.</i>

2
00:00:24,491 --> 00:00:26,007
It's been nearly
a decade...

3
00:00:26,159 --> 00:00:28,857
...since the best-selling autobiography
<i>Under the Hood...</i>

4
00:00:29,029 --> 00:00:32,226
...revealed secrets of the original band
of masked adventurers...

5
00:00:32,399 --> 00:00:34,390
...the new Minutemen.

6
00:00:34,667 --> 00:00:37,932
In 1975, when <i>The Culpeper Minute</i>
was new to the airwaves...

7
00:00:38,104 --> 00:00:40,971
...we profiled the author of
<i>Under the Hood,</i> Hollis Mason...

8
00:00:41,141 --> 00:00:43,837
...the former adventurer
known as Nite Owl.

9
00:00:44,010 --> 00:00:48,743
When my original report aired in 1975,
the Keene Act had not yet been passed.

10
00:00:48,915 --> 00:00:53,079
Now, this controversial bill outlawed all
costumed adventurers and masked heroes.

11
00:00:53,653 --> 00:00:57,521
Given our current climate of unrest
around the subject of masked justice...

12
00:00:57,690 --> 00:01:01,524
...we thought it would be interesting
to revisit that original episode...

13
00:01:01,694 --> 00:01:04,254
...as a reminder of where
the whole phenomena...

14
00:01:04,431 --> 00:01:06,922
...of costumed heroics began.

15
00:01:12,072 --> 00:01:16,634
Tonight we're talking with Hollis Mason
about his autobiography, <i>Under the Hood.</i>

16
00:01:16,810 --> 00:01:19,540
Hollis Mason's memoirs
revealed some of the secrets...

17
00:01:19,712 --> 00:01:21,043
...of the masked adventurers.

18
00:01:21,448 --> 00:01:27,080
I met with Hollis at one of his favorite
New York establishments, the Gunga Diner.

19
00:01:29,622 --> 00:01:31,715
Coming to New York at 12 years old...

20
00:01:31,891 --> 00:01:36,453
...it was, uh, fantastic for me
in a lot of ways.

21
00:01:37,230 --> 00:01:41,564
And my dad got a job
at Vernon's Auto Repair off 7th Avenue.

22
00:01:41,901 --> 00:01:45,064
- Now Mason's, right?
- Now Mason's. Yeah, yeah.

23
00:01:45,505 --> 00:01:46,563
Same place.

24
00:01:46,739 --> 00:01:50,106
CULPEPER: Yet you didn't follow in your
father's footsteps. You chose another path.

25
00:01:50,276 --> 00:01:52,369
MASON:
Well, yeah, when I was 23...

26
00:01:53,146 --> 00:01:56,240
...I joined the New York City
Police Department.

27
00:01:56,416 --> 00:02:00,045
And I think that that had a lot to do
with my grandfather...

28
00:02:00,220 --> 00:02:03,087
...and the values
that he'd instilled in me.

29
00:02:03,256 --> 00:02:07,056
Because for the first 12 years of my life,
I spent a lot of time with my granddad.

30
00:02:07,227 --> 00:02:10,219
He was always keen to impress upon me...

31
00:02:10,396 --> 00:02:16,926
...that country folk were morally healthier
than city folk, the way they lived.

32
00:02:17,103 --> 00:02:20,561
Of course you were competitive
in certain ways, but you were also...

33
00:02:20,740 --> 00:02:21,900
You helped each other.

34
00:02:22,075 --> 00:02:25,806
And it was kind of a moral value
that stuck with me.

35
00:02:25,979 --> 00:02:28,641
And when I first got to the city...

36
00:02:28,815 --> 00:02:34,219
...there were things I saw
that really filled me with disgust...

37
00:02:34,387 --> 00:02:39,222
...that I found a hard time shaking,
and, you know, some really...

38
00:02:39,659 --> 00:02:41,991
Some of it I still can't.

39
00:02:53,273 --> 00:02:56,299
What my grandfather gave me...

40
00:02:56,476 --> 00:02:59,240
...and what I was confronted with
in the city...

41
00:02:59,412 --> 00:03:03,314
When the distance between those things
got too great and I couldn't deal with it...

42
00:03:03,483 --> 00:03:08,716
...then I would go to my real other world,
the world of pulp-fiction novels.

43
00:03:10,890 --> 00:03:14,417
They described a world
of absolute values...

44
00:03:14,594 --> 00:03:17,529
...where what was good and true
was never in doubt.

45
00:03:17,697 --> 00:03:19,562
And evil was...

46
00:03:19,732 --> 00:03:23,327
Well, it received
its appropriate punishment.

47
00:03:23,503 --> 00:03:25,630
Is that how you've led your life, then?

48
00:03:25,805 --> 00:03:29,172
- That's what I've tried to do. Um...
- Mm-hm.

49
00:03:30,543 --> 00:03:31,840
Yeah.

50
00:03:32,011 --> 00:03:34,536
Hollis Mason, idealizing young cop...

51
00:03:34,714 --> 00:03:37,512
...trying to make sense
of granddad's country values...

52
00:03:37,684 --> 00:03:40,551
...and the grit of the big city
he finds himself living in.

53
00:03:40,720 --> 00:03:45,350
Soon enough, the police force and its brand
of justice is not enough for young Mason.

54
00:03:45,525 --> 00:03:49,552
Long a fan of pulp detective fiction
and comic-book heroics...

55
00:03:49,729 --> 00:03:52,254
...Mason did what others
only fantasize about.

56
00:03:52,432 --> 00:03:53,899
He made himself a disguise...

57
00:03:54,067 --> 00:03:56,831
...and set out in the nights
as a vigilante...

58
00:03:57,003 --> 00:03:59,528
...doling out justice on his own terms.

59
00:03:59,706 --> 00:04:03,267
What influenced this shift
in Mason's behavior?

60
00:04:04,944 --> 00:04:06,809
It's funny when you think about it.

61
00:04:08,881 --> 00:04:11,042
You know, I've heard all the...

62
00:04:11,217 --> 00:04:14,448
All the jokes and all the rumors
and all the innuendos.

63
00:04:14,654 --> 00:04:17,418
What it really comes down to for me...

64
00:04:17,590 --> 00:04:21,287
...is that I dressed up like an owl
and I fought crime...

65
00:04:23,229 --> 00:04:25,220
...because it was fun.

66
00:04:25,832 --> 00:04:28,266
And because it was the right thing to do.

67
00:04:29,202 --> 00:04:31,898
And because I darn well enjoyed it.

68
00:04:32,538 --> 00:04:33,869
[MASON CHUCKLES]

69
00:04:34,040 --> 00:04:38,977
I suppose it really started
to take shape for me in 1938.

70
00:04:39,145 --> 00:04:44,845
And on my beat there were a lot of kids
reading that first issue of <i>Action Comics.</i>

71
00:04:45,018 --> 00:04:47,213
I was so drawn, I couldn't help it.

72
00:04:47,387 --> 00:04:50,447
I asked one of the kids if I could
borrow it and take a look at it.

73
00:04:50,623 --> 00:04:54,184
And that first issue
of <i>Superman...</i>

74
00:04:54,627 --> 00:04:57,323
...wow, knocked me out.
- Mm-hm.

75
00:04:57,930 --> 00:05:02,230
Okay, Superman was your biggest
influence, and it was to a lot of kids.

76
00:05:02,402 --> 00:05:04,768
But you took it even further.

77
00:05:04,937 --> 00:05:08,464
MASON: Well, it all changed
when I opened the newspaper one day...

78
00:05:08,641 --> 00:05:14,602
...and I saw that these characters had
escaped from their four-color world...

79
00:05:14,781 --> 00:05:21,084
...and they were now in the factual
black-and-white world of the headlines.

80
00:05:23,556 --> 00:05:27,458
An attempted assault and robbery
was thwarted by a figure...

81
00:05:27,627 --> 00:05:30,755
...who supposedly dropped into
the alleyway from above...

82
00:05:30,930 --> 00:05:32,693
...with something over his face.

83
00:05:32,865 --> 00:05:36,198
And he then proceeded
to disarm the three attackers...

84
00:05:36,369 --> 00:05:40,396
...and beat them with such severity
that all three were hospitalized.

85
00:05:40,573 --> 00:05:44,634
The newspapers started calling him
Hooded Justice.

86
00:05:44,811 --> 00:05:49,407
And that was the first masked vigilante.

87
00:05:49,782 --> 00:05:53,775
And when I heard that story
I made up my mind right then...

88
00:05:53,953 --> 00:05:57,616
...I was gonna be the second.

89
00:05:57,790 --> 00:06:01,021
We have to take a break for our sponsors
now, but when we come back...

90
00:06:01,194 --> 00:06:05,494
...more from our 1975 story
on masked adventurers.

91
00:06:38,197 --> 00:06:39,824
Thank you for staying with us.

92
00:06:39,999 --> 00:06:43,196
We return now to our retrospective look
at <i>Under the Hood...</i>

93
00:06:43,369 --> 00:06:46,395
...and what these men and women
mean to us today.

94
00:06:47,974 --> 00:06:50,465
CULPEPER: Why did you come up
with the owl costume?

95
00:06:50,643 --> 00:06:52,543
MASON:
It really came together...

96
00:06:52,712 --> 00:06:56,648
...because of another cop that I was
working with in my station house.

97
00:06:56,816 --> 00:07:00,013
And he kept asking me
to go out for a beer after work.

98
00:07:00,186 --> 00:07:04,054
And I kept saying no, because, you know,
I wanted to train at night...

99
00:07:04,223 --> 00:07:06,214
...and get ready for my other career.

100
00:07:06,392 --> 00:07:09,054
And then he started
calling me "night owl."

101
00:07:09,228 --> 00:07:12,061
- You know, he was being sarcastic.
- Right.

102
00:07:12,231 --> 00:07:16,691
And I loved it.
I thought, "Well, that's it, Nite Owl."

103
00:07:16,869 --> 00:07:19,531
- So that's where the name came from?
- That's where it came from.

104
00:07:19,705 --> 00:07:23,004
So once I had the name, then I could
start thinking about the costume.

105
00:07:23,176 --> 00:07:27,806
Should it have a cape or no cape?
Should you have a mask or no mask?

106
00:07:27,980 --> 00:07:30,676
Eventually, I just boiled it down
to the basics.

107
00:07:30,850 --> 00:07:32,841
I needed a costume
where I was free to move.

108
00:07:33,019 --> 00:07:35,681
I needed to protect my body.
I needed to protect my head.

109
00:07:35,855 --> 00:07:38,415
And I needed to protect my identity.

110
00:07:38,591 --> 00:07:43,756
So I did this with a tunic
that was covered in leather and mail...

111
00:07:43,930 --> 00:07:45,397
...a kind of steel mesh.

112
00:07:45,565 --> 00:07:50,525
And I had a hood with...
It was leather and steel mesh again.

113
00:07:50,703 --> 00:07:54,503
And then briefs.
They were covered in the same mail.

114
00:07:54,674 --> 00:07:58,110
So I've got my hair covered
and all I need is a little mask.

115
00:07:58,277 --> 00:08:00,745
So I did it with this. This is the mask.

116
00:08:00,913 --> 00:08:04,440
I attached this mask with a spirit gum...

117
00:08:04,617 --> 00:08:08,485
...which is what actors use
to put on mustaches and beards.

118
00:08:08,654 --> 00:08:11,646
CULPEPER: It turned out, there were
several masked adventurers at the time.

119
00:08:11,824 --> 00:08:14,418
MASON: Yeah, about a month
after I made my debut...

120
00:08:14,594 --> 00:08:20,260
...the headlines were all about
a young woman called the Silhouette.

121
00:08:20,433 --> 00:08:25,461
She had exposed a crooked publisher
who was dealing in child pornography.

122
00:08:25,638 --> 00:08:32,134
And she gave him such a brutal beating.
Him and his two cameramen, right?

123
00:08:32,311 --> 00:08:34,871
Well, that was quite a story.

124
00:08:35,147 --> 00:08:37,377
From there it grew pretty quickly.

125
00:08:43,589 --> 00:08:47,025
There were stories
of a man dressed like a moth...

126
00:08:47,193 --> 00:08:50,219
...who could glide through the air.

127
00:08:53,833 --> 00:08:58,167
And then there was a story of a man
in a yellow boiler suit...

128
00:08:58,337 --> 00:09:02,865
...who was particularly brutal
and vicious.

129
00:09:03,442 --> 00:09:08,539
In 12 months of Hooded Justice's
dramatic entrance...

130
00:09:08,714 --> 00:09:12,445
...there were at least, oh,
seven other costumed vigilantes.

131
00:09:12,618 --> 00:09:15,917
There was Sally Jupiter,
who took the name of Silk Spectre.

132
00:09:16,088 --> 00:09:18,215
There was Dollar Bill,
there was Mothman...

133
00:09:18,391 --> 00:09:20,689
...there was the Silhouette,
there was Comedian.

134
00:09:20,860 --> 00:09:22,953
And, of course, there was me.

135
00:09:23,763 --> 00:09:26,664
Little that Mason told me
was not already in his book.

136
00:09:26,832 --> 00:09:31,667
So I turned to some of the other figures
from his world to find out more.

137
00:09:33,372 --> 00:09:35,932
She used her sexuality to fight crime...

138
00:09:36,108 --> 00:09:39,509
...and her crime fighting
to pursue a career on the silver screen.

139
00:09:39,679 --> 00:09:42,341
Now her daughter lives on in her image...

140
00:09:42,515 --> 00:09:45,484
...and life seemingly
has passed Sally Jupiter by.

141
00:09:46,052 --> 00:09:50,182
We joined her at her home
for the following exchange back in 1975.

142
00:09:52,491 --> 00:09:54,755
CULPEPER:
Why the name Silk Spectre?

143
00:09:54,927 --> 00:09:56,155
JUPITER:
You know, it's funny.

144
00:09:56,329 --> 00:10:00,231
Many people have hypothesized about
reasons why that might have come up.

145
00:10:00,399 --> 00:10:03,960
And in truth,
I wanted to find something mysterious...

146
00:10:04,136 --> 00:10:06,104
...something that had a good ring to it,
you know?

147
00:10:06,272 --> 00:10:10,766
And I felt that she should be somebody
who could slip out of your hands.

148
00:10:10,943 --> 00:10:14,106
Silk stockings, you know,
were very expensive at the time.

149
00:10:14,280 --> 00:10:18,011
And it just had a good ring to it,
I guess, is all I can really say.

150
00:10:18,184 --> 00:10:22,245
What were your motivations
in becoming a masked adventurer?

151
00:10:22,421 --> 00:10:24,946
I saw Hooded Justice...

152
00:10:25,124 --> 00:10:28,651
...and I think the idea of doing
something that was out of the normal...

153
00:10:28,828 --> 00:10:30,523
I never felt like I really fit in.

154
00:10:30,696 --> 00:10:35,633
And I think that becoming Silk Spectre
really made me feel actually more at home.

155
00:10:36,168 --> 00:10:41,697
Now, Silk Spectre is presented in fairly
racy imagery in posters and in comics.

156
00:10:41,874 --> 00:10:46,573
How do you deal with these,
what I call, visually degrading pictures?

157
00:10:46,746 --> 00:10:49,647
Oh, I never had a problem
with that sort of thing.

158
00:10:49,815 --> 00:10:53,444
I mean, you know, they always
referred to me as a sex symbol.

159
00:10:53,619 --> 00:10:55,951
And I have to say,
I'd rather be a symbol of that...

160
00:10:56,122 --> 00:10:59,057
...than a symbol for other things
they've got symbols of.

161
00:10:59,225 --> 00:11:00,715
You know what I mean?

162
00:11:00,893 --> 00:11:04,294
Jimmy Fantucci, a famous mobster,
I'm sure you've heard of him.

163
00:11:04,463 --> 00:11:08,092
He actually turned himself into the cops
because he couldn't shoot me.

164
00:11:08,267 --> 00:11:12,465
You know, as I said, I never shied away
from the way that I looked.

165
00:11:12,638 --> 00:11:14,731
And, in fact, it seemed in this case,
I could use it.

166
00:11:14,907 --> 00:11:18,775
Masked adventurers or whatever what you
wanna call them is all about commerce.

167
00:11:18,944 --> 00:11:23,381
You have to remember that this country
was founded on entertainment.

168
00:11:23,549 --> 00:11:26,347
And when I managed Sally,
the Silk Spectre...

169
00:11:26,519 --> 00:11:32,219
...we used her status as a costumed hero
to make lucrative deals of every kind.

170
00:11:32,391 --> 00:11:36,851
Movie deals, image licensing for pinups,
comic books, everything.

171
00:11:37,029 --> 00:11:41,295
It was a business strategy that corporations
picked up on almost immediately.

172
00:11:41,467 --> 00:11:44,163
Dollar Bill was originally
a star college athlete from Kansas...

173
00:11:44,336 --> 00:11:46,133
...hired by a major department store...

174
00:11:46,305 --> 00:11:48,865
...when they realized
that having their own superhero...

175
00:11:49,041 --> 00:11:52,135
...was an interesting publicity prospect.

176
00:11:52,311 --> 00:11:55,747
Still, I like to think that Sally and I
pioneered the concept.

177
00:11:55,915 --> 00:11:59,146
When you're trying to make a mark
in the world, you need help.

178
00:11:59,318 --> 00:12:03,118
You need someone
who can be sort of the cohesive factor...

179
00:12:03,289 --> 00:12:07,055
...in bringing the awareness to the public,
and he definitely did that.

180
00:12:07,226 --> 00:12:10,957
And I think, in fact, probably at the
expense of many people's agendas, really.

181
00:12:11,130 --> 00:12:13,257
I don't think you can make
value judgments...

182
00:12:13,432 --> 00:12:17,869
...on whether or not costumed heroes
are good or bad for society.

183
00:12:18,037 --> 00:12:20,870
That's like asking
if television is good or bad.

184
00:12:21,040 --> 00:12:22,871
The answer is that it's both.

185
00:12:23,042 --> 00:12:27,069
It was only really
when we got together...

186
00:12:27,613 --> 00:12:31,515
...that the problems started.

187
00:12:31,684 --> 00:12:33,845
The Minutemen, yeah.

188
00:12:34,019 --> 00:12:35,350
What a great idea.

189
00:12:35,521 --> 00:12:39,924
I wish I can take credit for it,
but I can't in good conscience.

190
00:12:40,092 --> 00:12:45,189
The way it happened was one day I got
a letter for Sally from Captain Metropolis.

191
00:12:45,364 --> 00:12:47,696
He said he wanted to get together
to discuss the idea...

192
00:12:47,867 --> 00:12:50,267
...of forming a group
of masked adventurers.

193
00:12:50,436 --> 00:12:54,236
At first, I thought he was using the idea
as a means to get her into bed.

194
00:12:54,406 --> 00:12:56,271
Then I did a little research...

195
00:12:56,442 --> 00:12:59,673
...and I learned that my concerns...

196
00:12:59,845 --> 00:13:03,542
...were, yeah, unfounded...

197
00:13:03,716 --> 00:13:06,844
...if you get my meaning.

198
00:13:07,052 --> 00:13:09,577
Lawrence made the Minutemen.

199
00:13:09,755 --> 00:13:12,747
If it wasn't for him
and his knack for publicity...

200
00:13:12,925 --> 00:13:16,884
I mean I think as someone in your
profession, you could probably understand...

201
00:13:17,062 --> 00:13:20,623
...that if we did this interview and no one
saw it, then, poof, it doesn't matter.

202
00:13:20,800 --> 00:13:23,564
SHEXNAYDER: I realized
that without the occasional gimmick...

203
00:13:23,736 --> 00:13:26,068
...to revitalize flagging public interest...

204
00:13:26,238 --> 00:13:28,900
...the fad of costumed heroes...

205
00:13:29,074 --> 00:13:31,804
...would eventually fade,
even the ones dressed like Sally.

206
00:13:31,977 --> 00:13:35,640
After some consideration I suggested
they take a large ad out in the <i>Gazette...</i>

207
00:13:35,815 --> 00:13:38,648
...asking for more mystery men
to come forward.

208
00:13:38,818 --> 00:13:42,276
And that's how
the Minutemen came to be.

209
00:13:42,955 --> 00:13:44,923
CULPEPER:
Now, when you first met The Comedian...

210
00:13:45,090 --> 00:13:47,149
...Nite Owl, Silhouette and the others...

211
00:13:47,326 --> 00:13:50,727
...what were your thoughts?
Were you intimidated?

212
00:13:50,896 --> 00:13:52,523
Was there a sense of relief?

213
00:13:52,698 --> 00:13:56,498
Oh, it was an incredibly
exhilarating time, I have to say.

214
00:13:56,669 --> 00:13:59,832
I think we all felt like
we were part of a family...

215
00:14:00,005 --> 00:14:02,803
...that we had found sort of a place...

216
00:14:02,975 --> 00:14:05,603
...where we could feel like
we actually were of value.

217
00:14:05,778 --> 00:14:08,269
Everyone brought
something different to the Minutemen.

218
00:14:08,447 --> 00:14:11,814
But somehow when we were together
there was a bonding feeling...

219
00:14:11,984 --> 00:14:14,384
...that we all believed
in what we were doing.

220
00:14:14,553 --> 00:14:18,614
Now, the reason I say "relief" is because
many of the people back in those days...

221
00:14:18,791 --> 00:14:22,591
...thought that you were all
rather bizarre, abnormal individuals...

222
00:14:22,761 --> 00:14:25,662
...running around in children's costumes.

223
00:14:25,831 --> 00:14:27,162
JUPITER:
We were just people.

224
00:14:27,333 --> 00:14:30,268
And everyone did have absolutely
different politics.

225
00:14:30,436 --> 00:14:33,132
Some of us were in it for fame.
Some for power.

226
00:14:33,305 --> 00:14:37,264
Some to possibly hide
from the rest of the world.

227
00:14:37,443 --> 00:14:41,436
But in the end of the day, our politics
really didn't get in the way too much...

228
00:14:41,614 --> 00:14:44,310
...of what we wanted to be there to do,
which was good.

229
00:14:44,483 --> 00:14:49,352
We did too much good in our respective
communities just to be written off.

230
00:14:49,521 --> 00:14:52,422
We were all attempting
through our personal efforts...

231
00:14:52,591 --> 00:14:57,722
...to make our country
a better and a safer place to live.

232
00:14:57,897 --> 00:15:01,094
Clearly, Hollis Mason is a man
who makes no apologies...

233
00:15:01,267 --> 00:15:03,827
...for the life he's lived
or the decisions he's made.

234
00:15:04,003 --> 00:15:07,439
But is his own personal moral code
enough justification...

235
00:15:07,606 --> 00:15:10,803
...for donning a mask
and dispensing vigilante justice?

236
00:15:10,976 --> 00:15:13,968
I went out and asked around
to get a better sense...

237
00:15:14,146 --> 00:15:17,707
...of how you, the people,
felt about masked heroes.

238
00:15:24,056 --> 00:15:25,717
MAN 1:
I don't know.

239
00:15:25,891 --> 00:15:27,756
I get a lot of customers that are cops.

240
00:15:27,927 --> 00:15:30,361
Guys that come by and pay
for a pack of smokes from me...

241
00:15:30,529 --> 00:15:34,124
...and they tell me
that these masked adventurers...

242
00:15:34,300 --> 00:15:36,928
...they're making the job more difficult.

243
00:15:38,404 --> 00:15:40,065
MAN 2:
What do I think of them?

244
00:15:40,239 --> 00:15:42,799
They've just about destroyed my business,
I can tell you that.

245
00:15:44,677 --> 00:15:47,441
They maim my customers.

246
00:15:47,646 --> 00:15:52,083
They like to break fingers. They think
it's funny. Yeah. They're dangerous.

247
00:15:52,518 --> 00:15:55,180
But then on the other hand,
what if we hadn't had...

248
00:15:55,354 --> 00:15:58,187
...that Dr. Manhattan guy
on our side, huh?

249
00:15:58,357 --> 00:16:01,849
I mean, I know it's inconceivable to us,
now knowing what we know...

250
00:16:02,127 --> 00:16:05,619
...but who's to say that things wouldn't
have gone the same in Vietnam...

251
00:16:05,798 --> 00:16:07,163
...without them?

252
00:16:07,333 --> 00:16:09,028
Losing that war.

253
00:16:09,201 --> 00:16:10,793
That would've destroyed our country.

254
00:16:11,937 --> 00:16:15,338
More on costumed adventurers
and the controversy surrounding them...

255
00:16:15,507 --> 00:16:18,237
...after this word from our sponsors.

256
00:16:19,578 --> 00:16:22,411
