<i>The Seiko liquid crystal chronograph.</i>

263
00:16:39,999 --> 00:16:43,264
<i>Only one of Seiko's</i>
<i>superb digital quartz watches.</i>

264
00:16:49,742 --> 00:16:52,210
Welcome back,
and thank you for watching.

265
00:16:52,378 --> 00:16:57,111
In our current climate, the relevance
of masked adventurers, the Watchmen...

266
00:16:57,282 --> 00:16:59,375
...is more in question than ever before.

267
00:16:59,551 --> 00:17:01,815
We continue now
with our look back at a show...

268
00:17:01,987 --> 00:17:04,046
...in which we discussed
<i>Under the Hood...</i>

269
00:17:04,223 --> 00:17:08,887
...a memoir of original masked hero
The Nite Owl, née Hollis Mason.

270
00:17:09,061 --> 00:17:12,258
A book which precipitated
many of the questions we have today...

271
00:17:12,431 --> 00:17:17,391
...about these men and women who act
apart from our prescribed laws of justice.

272
00:17:30,082 --> 00:17:34,678
Certainly there are many costumed heroes
who would make for fascinating study.

273
00:17:34,853 --> 00:17:37,481
I spoke with psychiatrist William Long...

274
00:17:37,656 --> 00:17:39,681
...to gain some professional insight.

275
00:17:39,858 --> 00:17:42,486
You know, it's an interesting question.

276
00:17:43,495 --> 00:17:46,555
Mostly, in the prison,
I work with criminals.

277
00:17:46,732 --> 00:17:50,634
So my perception is slightly skewed.

278
00:17:50,836 --> 00:17:54,169
I think certainly
there are masked heroes...

279
00:17:54,339 --> 00:17:57,740
...and superhumans, like Dr. Manhattan...

280
00:17:57,910 --> 00:17:59,935
...that just want to do good.

281
00:18:00,112 --> 00:18:04,879
I think there are others
that are nothing more than criminals...

282
00:18:05,050 --> 00:18:07,610
...who used this as a means...

283
00:18:07,786 --> 00:18:12,086
...to justify their violent tendencies.

284
00:18:12,257 --> 00:18:18,218
The only masked heroes
that pose an actual threat...

285
00:18:18,730 --> 00:18:23,190
...are the relatively few
borderline sociopaths...

286
00:18:23,368 --> 00:18:26,804
...that actually believe
that they are doing good.

287
00:18:26,972 --> 00:18:28,837
Beneath that mask...

288
00:18:30,309 --> 00:18:32,573
...they're just like you and me...

289
00:18:33,078 --> 00:18:37,344
...with hopes and desires, fears...

290
00:18:37,516 --> 00:18:39,848
...love.

291
00:18:40,786 --> 00:18:43,254
I hope that one day...

292
00:18:43,422 --> 00:18:48,416
...I can psychoanalyze
one of these masked heroes.

293
00:18:48,994 --> 00:18:50,825
That would be something.

294
00:18:51,630 --> 00:18:53,723
It seems a bygone era to us now.

295
00:18:53,899 --> 00:18:56,231
The heady days of the roaring '40s.

296
00:18:56,401 --> 00:18:59,632
People were eager for distraction,
hungry for a fix of drama.

297
00:18:59,805 --> 00:19:02,968
What better than a group
of self-designed superheroes...

298
00:19:03,142 --> 00:19:06,475
...to act out an exaggerated
street theater of crime fighting.

299
00:19:06,645 --> 00:19:09,842
And in a world populated
by supervillains...

300
00:19:10,015 --> 00:19:11,607
...why not?

301
00:19:11,783 --> 00:19:14,684
There was the notorious
Moloch the Mystic...

302
00:19:14,853 --> 00:19:20,155
...using the sideshow novelty of the magic
show to front his one-man wave of terror.

303
00:19:20,325 --> 00:19:23,852
Later, of course, came modern
supervillains like Big Figure...

304
00:19:24,029 --> 00:19:28,295
...the diminutive master criminal now
serving a life sentence in the city jail.

305
00:19:35,207 --> 00:19:37,368
You think I'm the menace.

306
00:19:37,876 --> 00:19:41,334
I'm not the one wearing a mask.
I got nothing to hide.

307
00:19:41,747 --> 00:19:44,739
What kind of person is that?
Wear a mask?

308
00:19:47,819 --> 00:19:51,220
I'm a respectable businessman.

309
00:19:52,090 --> 00:19:54,524
CULPEPER:
It wasn't easy finding Moloch the Mystic.

310
00:19:54,693 --> 00:19:57,161
But then again, well,
it wasn't too difficult.

311
00:19:57,329 --> 00:20:01,390
You see, Moloch, like so many infamous
figures of our postwar past...

312
00:20:01,567 --> 00:20:03,831
...had simply gone into civilian life.

313
00:20:04,937 --> 00:20:06,336
MOLOCH:
I was a younger man then.

314
00:20:06,505 --> 00:20:08,166
I was rebellious.

315
00:20:08,941 --> 00:20:12,707
Like these gangs you see around,
the Knot Tops.

316
00:20:12,878 --> 00:20:16,678
When you live in a world
with superhuman authority figures...

317
00:20:16,848 --> 00:20:19,612
...and you wanna rebel,
you have to rebel on a larger scale.

318
00:20:19,785 --> 00:20:23,186
You have to escalate things, you see.

319
00:20:23,355 --> 00:20:25,152
So...

320
00:20:25,524 --> 00:20:29,119
...if you grow up in a world
with superheroes and you wanna rebel...

321
00:20:29,294 --> 00:20:33,287
...you have to become a supervillain.

322
00:20:35,601 --> 00:20:39,970
So, yeah, I think society is better off
without the superheroes...

323
00:20:40,138 --> 00:20:45,667
...because that means there's no need
for any supervillains either.

324
00:20:48,880 --> 00:20:50,643
MASON:
Thank you. Thanks.

325
00:20:52,217 --> 00:20:56,984
You know, it didn't last, oh, 10 years.

326
00:20:57,155 --> 00:21:01,854
When the '50s came, the whole perception
of costumed adventurers...

327
00:21:02,027 --> 00:21:04,928
...you know, changed, you know?

328
00:21:05,264 --> 00:21:06,458
It was a fad, yeah.

329
00:21:06,632 --> 00:21:10,261
And the fad was dying out
and we were dying with it.

330
00:21:10,435 --> 00:21:11,663
[CHUCKLES]

331
00:21:12,971 --> 00:21:14,529
Sally...

332
00:21:14,706 --> 00:21:16,901
...well, she got pregnant
and she left.

333
00:21:17,442 --> 00:21:20,707
The rest of us,
we were forced to testify...

334
00:21:20,879 --> 00:21:23,279
...before the House Un-American
Activities Committee.

335
00:21:23,448 --> 00:21:24,972
It was a witch hunt.

336
00:21:25,150 --> 00:21:29,519
We were all forced to reveal
our identities...

337
00:21:29,688 --> 00:21:32,088
...to one of its representatives.

338
00:21:32,257 --> 00:21:35,158
I am Captain Metropolis
from the Minutemen.

339
00:21:35,327 --> 00:21:37,227
MASON:
Now, luckily, with Captain Metropolis...

340
00:21:37,396 --> 00:21:39,523
...having such an outstanding
military record...

341
00:21:39,698 --> 00:21:41,791
...and with my own service
in the police force...

342
00:21:41,967 --> 00:21:45,630
...we both were more or less
cleared of suspicion right away.

343
00:21:47,005 --> 00:21:51,408
Mothman met with more difficulty,
mostly because of the left-wing friends...

344
00:21:51,576 --> 00:21:54,943
...that he'd cultivated
during his student days.

345
00:21:55,147 --> 00:21:56,808
Now, he's eventually cleared...

346
00:21:56,982 --> 00:22:01,510
...but the investigations,
they were so lengthy and so ruthless...

347
00:22:01,687 --> 00:22:04,349
...that I think that
the pressure he was under...

348
00:22:04,523 --> 00:22:06,718
...it exacerbated his drinking problem...

349
00:22:06,892 --> 00:22:10,919
...and it caused
his eventual mental breakdown.

350
00:22:18,136 --> 00:22:20,331
Hooded Justice...

351
00:22:20,505 --> 00:22:21,836
...refused to testify...

352
00:22:22,007 --> 00:22:26,205
...on the grounds that he was not prepared
to reveal his true identity to anybody.

353
00:22:26,378 --> 00:22:28,471
And when they pressed him...

354
00:22:29,114 --> 00:22:30,911
...he disappeared.

355
00:22:31,416 --> 00:22:33,714
And I really respect him for that.

356
00:22:34,353 --> 00:22:36,253
He was the reason
I became the Nite Owl...

357
00:22:36,421 --> 00:22:42,189
...and I don't know to this day
who he was behind that mask.

358
00:22:42,361 --> 00:22:43,453
Isn't that something?

359
00:22:43,628 --> 00:22:45,095
[CHUCKLES]

360
00:22:45,263 --> 00:22:48,858
I understand that you wanted to leave
the Minutemen because you got pregnant.

361
00:22:49,034 --> 00:22:51,059
Is that the reason?
Was there any other reasons...

362
00:22:51,236 --> 00:22:54,228
...that you retired from the Minutemen?

363
00:22:55,440 --> 00:22:57,601
JUPITER: You know,
sometimes it's just time to move on.

364
00:22:57,776 --> 00:23:01,177
I think I would've stayed longer,
had I not gotten pregnant.

365
00:23:01,346 --> 00:23:05,715
But it was... You know, life gives you those
little signs of when to take the door out.

366
00:23:05,884 --> 00:23:07,818
And that seemed to be the one.

367
00:23:07,986 --> 00:23:12,650
In his biography, Hollis alleged that you
were sexually assaulted by The Comedian.

368
00:23:12,824 --> 00:23:15,122
Yet you've never said anything
about this.

369
00:23:15,594 --> 00:23:17,084
Hmm.

370
00:23:18,430 --> 00:23:21,194
Well, why should I break
a lifetime's habit now, right?

371
00:23:21,366 --> 00:23:22,526
[CHUCKLES]

372
00:23:22,701 --> 00:23:27,968
I can't blame you for asking
as a reporter, but, yes, it's...

373
00:23:28,140 --> 00:23:29,164
No comment.

374
00:23:29,341 --> 00:23:35,143
How much did the incident
between Sally Jupiter and The Comedian...

375
00:23:35,313 --> 00:23:37,304
...affect your decision
to hang up the mask?

376
00:23:37,883 --> 00:23:41,717
Well, that had lot to do with it, yeah.

377
00:23:43,588 --> 00:23:46,489
I think once you realize
that some of your teammates...

378
00:23:46,658 --> 00:23:49,286
...are just as depraved...

379
00:23:49,461 --> 00:23:54,524
...and twisted as the criminals
you're going after...

380
00:23:56,234 --> 00:23:57,929
Yeah.

381
00:23:58,470 --> 00:24:01,098
That had a lot to do with why I quit.

382
00:24:01,273 --> 00:24:03,332
There's no truth to that rumor.

383
00:24:03,508 --> 00:24:05,271
If something like that had happened...

384
00:24:05,444 --> 00:24:11,076
...don't you think I would have advised
Sally to have pressed criminal charges?

385
00:24:11,249 --> 00:24:13,843
She was my best client.
My biggest earner.

386
00:24:14,386 --> 00:24:17,446
I would never allow something like that
to go unpunished.

387
00:24:17,622 --> 00:24:19,590
It's nothing more than sensationalism.

388
00:24:20,125 --> 00:24:21,683
Self-promotion.

389
00:24:21,860 --> 00:24:24,420
Hollis Mason wants to sell more books.

390
00:24:24,596 --> 00:24:27,030
CULPEPER:
The Comedian declined to comment.

391
00:24:27,199 --> 00:24:31,135
Get that thing out of my face
before I put my cigar out in your eye.

392
00:24:32,370 --> 00:24:34,804
<i>Under the Hood</i>
is a fantastic book.

393
00:24:34,973 --> 00:24:37,100
You know, he's one of my customers,
you know.

394
00:24:37,275 --> 00:24:39,266
I see him all the time.

395
00:24:39,611 --> 00:24:44,241
It's funny about this superhero thing,
you know, it's a very fine line.

396
00:24:44,416 --> 00:24:46,384
And when you got somebody
like the Nite Owl...

397
00:24:46,551 --> 00:24:50,749
...who is your quintessential superhero,
because outside you get this guy...

398
00:24:50,922 --> 00:24:53,447
...who dresses up
and does all the kaboom-kabang stuff...

399
00:24:53,625 --> 00:24:56,389
...but inside he's a cop.

400
00:24:56,561 --> 00:24:59,758
So he's a guy who knows what's true blue.
You know what I mean?

401
00:24:59,931 --> 00:25:02,126
He's not into these
kind of artsy-fartsy things.

402
00:25:02,300 --> 00:25:04,063
He's a great man.

403
00:25:04,603 --> 00:25:06,002
So...

404
00:25:06,171 --> 00:25:07,661
...I don't know.

405
00:25:07,839 --> 00:25:13,744
Hard to say whether these masked-hero
types are a good or a bad thing...

406
00:25:13,912 --> 00:25:17,143
...you know, in the final analysis.

407
00:25:17,315 --> 00:25:20,478
It's interesting to note
that back in 1975...

408
00:25:20,652 --> 00:25:23,587
...people were still very much divided
as to whether or not...

409
00:25:23,755 --> 00:25:28,385
...the so-called costumed adventurers
were a benefit or a detriment to society.

410
00:25:28,560 --> 00:25:30,721
Given the events
after this interview aired...

411
00:25:30,896 --> 00:25:34,263
...perhaps Hollis Mason's retirement
came at the perfect time.

412
00:25:34,432 --> 00:25:38,232
We'll hear more from Hollis Mason
after this commercial break.

413
