<i>Get Sani-Flush, powder or liquid.</i>

423
00:26:09,935 --> 00:26:12,802
Continuing now with my interview
of Hollis Mason.

424
00:26:12,971 --> 00:26:15,166
We're talking about
costumed adventurers.

425
00:26:15,340 --> 00:26:18,104
He's been called
the Eighth Wonder of the World.

426
00:26:18,276 --> 00:26:20,972
Our national treasure. Our greatest hope.

427
00:26:21,146 --> 00:26:24,309
But Dr. Manhattan is also viewed
as a freak of nature.

428
00:26:24,482 --> 00:26:29,977
His power is so great as to illicit fear
not only in our enemies but in ourselves.

429
00:26:30,155 --> 00:26:33,318
Before he was the radiating blue
superbeing he is today...

430
00:26:33,491 --> 00:26:37,222
...he was Jon Osterman,
physicist, son of a watchmaker.

431
00:26:37,395 --> 00:26:42,094
A man with friendships,
loves, common family values.

432
00:26:42,267 --> 00:26:44,633
One of his friends
and, in fact, colleagues...

433
00:26:44,803 --> 00:26:47,397
...who continues to work
with Dr. Manhattan today...

434
00:26:47,572 --> 00:26:50,166
...is an esteemed physicist
in his own right...

435
00:26:50,342 --> 00:26:51,434
...Wally Weaver.

436
00:26:51,610 --> 00:26:54,272
We went to Weaver's lab
and had the following conversation.

437
00:26:54,446 --> 00:26:57,415
Well, I think...

438
00:26:57,616 --> 00:26:59,846
...heroes of all kinds are a good thing.

439
00:27:00,018 --> 00:27:04,455
And I'm talking about the brave men
and women of our Armed Forces.

440
00:27:04,623 --> 00:27:08,252
I'm talking about the policemen
and the firefighters.

441
00:27:08,426 --> 00:27:13,762
I'm talking about the scientists
and the doctors. And, uh...

442
00:27:14,132 --> 00:27:16,999
Yeah, I'd include masked heroes...

443
00:27:17,168 --> 00:27:19,636
...in that group
that's a benefit to society too.

444
00:27:19,804 --> 00:27:21,362
Jon is...

445
00:27:21,539 --> 00:27:25,066
I'm sorry. Dr. Manhattan...

446
00:27:25,510 --> 00:27:27,705
...is something else entirely.

447
00:27:28,546 --> 00:27:34,416
I'm writing a book about how he's changed
the geopolitical landscape forever...

448
00:27:35,086 --> 00:27:38,817
...essentially making the very idea...

449
00:27:38,990 --> 00:27:41,925
...of war obsolete.

450
00:27:43,628 --> 00:27:49,225
MASON: You know, the first thing
was absolute disbelief.

451
00:27:49,401 --> 00:27:51,995
Well, of course, as you know,
there was elation too.

452
00:27:52,170 --> 00:27:55,697
I mean, it was like Santa Claus
was alive and thriving.

453
00:27:55,874 --> 00:27:58,104
But the fear...

454
00:27:59,144 --> 00:28:02,545
It was a terrible fear...

455
00:28:02,714 --> 00:28:06,650
...and an uncertainty
that went right to your core.

456
00:28:06,818 --> 00:28:09,218
I certainly understood
how an old car feels...

457
00:28:09,387 --> 00:28:12,379
...when it sees a new car,
a new model come rolling out.

458
00:28:12,557 --> 00:28:14,047
[CHUCKLES]

459
00:28:14,659 --> 00:28:16,286
But it was more than that.

460
00:28:16,461 --> 00:28:22,889
You know, I think I can boil the feeling
down to three words, really. It's:

461
00:28:23,068 --> 00:28:25,195
We've been replaced.

462
00:28:25,403 --> 00:28:28,634
And I don't just mean
the masked adventurers.

463
00:28:28,807 --> 00:28:31,970
I mean, humanity.

464
00:28:32,877 --> 00:28:34,811
We've been replaced.

465
00:28:38,049 --> 00:28:41,348
Hollis always did have
a flair for the dramatic.

466
00:28:41,519 --> 00:28:44,545
There is no doubt that it was
an absolute shock to all of us.

467
00:28:44,723 --> 00:28:47,590
The fact that anything could exist
like Dr. Manhattan.

468
00:28:47,759 --> 00:28:52,025
I mean, this was something
out of the realm of concept for us.

469
00:28:52,197 --> 00:28:55,064
But we will always have a need
for humanity...

470
00:28:55,233 --> 00:29:00,728
...and as much as we expand
and grow technologically, it's...

471
00:29:00,905 --> 00:29:03,032
We still need human contact, you know?

472
00:29:03,675 --> 00:29:06,838
People have always misinterpreted
what I said about Jon.

473
00:29:07,378 --> 00:29:12,839
I wasn't comparing him to God.
I wasn't saying he was a god.

474
00:29:13,017 --> 00:29:14,609
I just...

475
00:29:15,720 --> 00:29:18,120
Just wish I wouldn't have
ever said that.

476
00:29:18,490 --> 00:29:21,789
Bottom line is this: Jon is still Jon.

477
00:29:22,393 --> 00:29:24,361
At his core...

478
00:29:25,396 --> 00:29:27,227
...he's still a man.

479
00:29:28,366 --> 00:29:33,326
Well, take what I said about
supervillains being a direct response...

480
00:29:33,505 --> 00:29:35,473
...to the appearance of superheroes...

481
00:29:35,640 --> 00:29:39,007
...and apply that
to the current scenario.

482
00:29:39,177 --> 00:29:43,204
If you have a being that can destroy...

483
00:29:43,381 --> 00:29:44,939
...with a single thought...

484
00:29:45,116 --> 00:29:47,346
...then the terrifying thing
is that there is...

485
00:29:47,519 --> 00:29:52,786
...or there soon will be, a counterpoint
or an adversary to that being.

486
00:29:52,957 --> 00:29:57,951
The universe has a way of finding
its own equilibrium, its own level.

487
00:29:59,397 --> 00:30:05,063
What worries me is that Dr. Manhattan's
nemesis will be arriving soon.

488
00:30:09,707 --> 00:30:12,232
Of course,
some of these masked adventurers...

489
00:30:12,410 --> 00:30:14,970
...never stopped practicing
their unique craft.

490
00:30:15,146 --> 00:30:19,082
Eventually time moved forward to a point
where their presence was again welcomed...

491
00:30:19,250 --> 00:30:21,548
...and some would say sorely needed.

492
00:30:22,120 --> 00:30:24,179
Big city streets
festered with violence...

493
00:30:24,355 --> 00:30:26,516
...intimidation and rampant crime.

494
00:30:26,691 --> 00:30:30,559
A perfect environment
for a new breed of masked hero to emerge.

495
00:30:30,728 --> 00:30:32,992
Of course, I speak of the Watchmen.

496
00:30:33,565 --> 00:30:37,695
Now, with the Cold War escalating
and the presence of a truly super being...

497
00:30:37,869 --> 00:30:39,962
...at the forefront
of our national defense...

498
00:30:40,138 --> 00:30:44,131
...a growing fear and restlessness
seems to permeate the population.

499
00:30:44,809 --> 00:30:47,471
Only this time,
the fear is not of the criminals...

500
00:30:47,645 --> 00:30:49,670
...but of the crime fighters themselves.

501
00:30:49,848 --> 00:30:53,306
Senator Keene surely thinks
that the time has come to put an end...

502
00:30:53,484 --> 00:30:54,883
...to masked adventuring.

503
00:30:55,053 --> 00:30:59,717
His suggested new laws would effectively
clip the wings of these costumed heroes...

504
00:30:59,891 --> 00:31:01,483
...making them hang up their masks...

505
00:31:01,659 --> 00:31:05,561
...and preventing them from practicing
vigilante justice in our fair streets.

506
00:31:06,030 --> 00:31:09,898
Senator Keene is an opportunistic...

507
00:31:11,269 --> 00:31:13,100
...cipher.

508
00:31:13,271 --> 00:31:15,796
He has no idea what he's talking about.

509
00:31:15,974 --> 00:31:18,465
The real problem
are the police departments.

510
00:31:18,643 --> 00:31:23,444
If they would take a little bit more
of what these masked heroes have...

511
00:31:23,615 --> 00:31:26,516
...then we wouldn't need people
like Senator Keene...

512
00:31:26,684 --> 00:31:28,151
...in the Senate in the first place.

513
00:31:29,420 --> 00:31:31,183
What do I think about Senator Keene?

514
00:31:31,356 --> 00:31:33,415
Listen, I work down here every day.

515
00:31:33,591 --> 00:31:36,890
Whenever I'm in trouble, whenever
somebody's down here beating me up...

516
00:31:37,061 --> 00:31:39,791
...and I yell for help, I don't care
who comes to save my butt.

517
00:31:39,964 --> 00:31:43,422
I don't care if it's a superhero.
I don't care if it's a cop.

518
00:31:43,601 --> 00:31:46,764
As long as somebody comes
when I'm yelling "help."

519
00:31:47,171 --> 00:31:48,263
You understand?

520
00:31:48,439 --> 00:31:50,634
People have...

521
00:31:50,909 --> 00:31:53,275
...a need for...

522
00:31:53,444 --> 00:31:55,435
...an everyday hero.

523
00:31:55,813 --> 00:31:58,077
Masked or otherwise.

524
00:31:58,249 --> 00:32:00,080
And, uh...

525
00:32:02,220 --> 00:32:06,350
...people who know right from wrong...

526
00:32:06,524 --> 00:32:10,187
...will always be in demand.

527
00:32:23,675 --> 00:32:28,305
So I want to get a little personal here
for the moment.

528
00:32:28,513 --> 00:32:30,003
You never married. Why is that?

529
00:32:32,750 --> 00:32:35,810
- Um...
- Thank you.

530
00:32:35,987 --> 00:32:39,514
Well, I suppose if there's any one reason
why I never got married...

531
00:32:39,691 --> 00:32:41,215
...it was because...

532
00:32:42,393 --> 00:32:46,193
...well, Sally Jupiter was taken.

533
00:32:46,364 --> 00:32:48,332
I don't think...

534
00:32:48,499 --> 00:32:51,491
...it's any great secret
that I had a thing for her.

535
00:32:51,669 --> 00:32:53,830
Half the male population did.

536
00:32:54,005 --> 00:32:58,169
By the time I'd rustled up the courage
to ask her out on a proper date...

537
00:32:58,843 --> 00:33:00,868
...she was already married
to her manager.

538
00:33:01,446 --> 00:33:03,107
[CHUCKLES]

539
00:33:04,482 --> 00:33:06,814
It's kind of funny when you think of it.

540
00:33:07,185 --> 00:33:12,384
I dress up as an owl
and risk my life on a daily basis...

541
00:33:12,957 --> 00:33:16,825
...but when it came to
asking a girl out...

542
00:33:16,995 --> 00:33:19,589
...it was more than I could manage.

543
00:33:19,797 --> 00:33:24,131
Sadly, I think our marriage
was doomed from the start.

544
00:33:24,302 --> 00:33:28,739
My professional position in Sally's life
made it very difficult to be a good husband.

545
00:33:28,906 --> 00:33:30,737
It was my job as her manager...

546
00:33:30,908 --> 00:33:34,241
...to not only accept the fact
that men were attracted to her...

547
00:33:34,412 --> 00:33:36,846
...but to build on that attraction...

548
00:33:37,815 --> 00:33:39,976
...to prey upon it.

549
00:33:46,758 --> 00:33:48,385
Hollis was very important to you.

550
00:33:48,559 --> 00:33:50,618
He was a very important person
in your life, correct?

551
00:33:50,795 --> 00:33:51,819
Absolutely.

552
00:33:51,996 --> 00:33:55,056
- You stay in contact with each other today?
- We do. We do.

553
00:33:55,233 --> 00:33:57,531
Not as much as I would like, I must say.

554
00:33:57,702 --> 00:34:00,000
You know, your life takes you
in different directions...

555
00:34:00,171 --> 00:34:03,607
...but that was really a magical,
magical time...

556
00:34:03,775 --> 00:34:07,267
...and we do like to talk about
the old times when we get together.

557
00:34:07,879 --> 00:34:09,779
You know, I think...

558
00:34:10,214 --> 00:34:12,648
I think I still have some kind of...

559
00:34:12,817 --> 00:34:15,718
...half-baked idea that...

560
00:34:16,254 --> 00:34:20,384
...Nite Owl and, uh...

561
00:34:21,059 --> 00:34:25,223
...Silk Spectre are gonna end up
together one day.

562
00:34:33,638 --> 00:34:34,969
Hm.

563
00:34:36,707 --> 00:34:39,073
When we originally spoke
with Hollis Mason...

564
00:34:39,243 --> 00:34:42,303
...he believed that the legacy
he'd begun as the Nite Owl...

565
00:34:42,480 --> 00:34:44,880
...along with other members
of the masked-hero community...

566
00:34:45,049 --> 00:34:47,108
...would live on for years to come.

567
00:34:47,285 --> 00:34:50,721
He could not have known
how wrong he was.

568
00:34:54,058 --> 00:34:58,552
This has been a nostalgic look back
at a colorful time in this nation's past...

569
00:34:58,729 --> 00:35:01,789
...when we turned to flamboyant heroes
with cartoonish outfits...

570
00:35:01,966 --> 00:35:03,331
...for our moral outlook.

571
00:35:03,501 --> 00:35:05,901
In the post-Keene Act world
we now live in...

572
00:35:06,070 --> 00:35:08,630
...the masked heroes
are as outdated and irrelevant...

573
00:35:08,806 --> 00:35:12,674
...as the old beat-up wrecks
that Hollis Mason works on in his garage.

574
00:35:12,844 --> 00:35:16,837
We hope that you have found this look back
at the history of costumed adventurers...

575
00:35:17,014 --> 00:35:19,482
...both enlightening and informative.

576
00:35:19,650 --> 00:35:22,517
I'm Larry Culpeper
for <i>The Culpeper Minute.</i>

577
